  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(25) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "But Hezekiah.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—For Hezekiah’s pride, see the account of his reception of the Babylonian embassy (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Kings 20:12-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Isaiah 39).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "According to the benefit done unto him.—In his illness he promised to walk humbly all his days (Isaiah 38:15); but when he had recovered, “his heart was lifted up.”",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "According to the benefit done unto him.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—In his illness he promised to walk humbly all his days (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 38:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "); but when he had recovered, “his heart was lifted up.”",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Therefore there was wrath upon him.—And wrath fell upon him. The token of this was seen in Isaiah’s prophetic rebuke, foretelling that the royal treasures would be carried away to Babylon, and that some of Hezekiah’s sons would be eunuchs in the palace there (2Kings 20:16-18; Isaiah 39:5-7).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Therefore there was wrath upon him.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "And wrath fell upon him.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " The token of this was seen in Isaiah’s prophetic rebuke, foretelling that the royal treasures would be carried away to Babylon, and that some of Hezekiah’s sons would be eunuchs in the palace there (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Kings 20:16-18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 39:5-7",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ").",
            "children": []
          }
