  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "\"But Hezekiah rendered not according to the benefit unto him, for his heart was proud.\" In his sickness he had promised to walk in humility all his days (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 38:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "): yet he became proud after his recovery; and his pride showed itself especially in his showing all his treasures to the Babylonian embassy, in idle trust in them and in the resources at his command (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 20:12-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 39:1-4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). \"And there was wrath upon him, and upon Judah and Jerusalem,\" which participated in the king's sentiments (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 19:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 27:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Isaiah proclaimed this wrath to him in the prophecy that all the treasures of the king would be carried away to Babylon, and that some of his sons should become courtiers of the king of Babylon (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 20:16-18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 39:5-7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), to which we should perhaps also reckon the threatening prophecy in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Micah 3:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
